│ "thoughts": "1. Understanding the Issue:\nThe provided IR crashes opt with an │
│ assertion in MemorySSAUpdater::fixupDefs: MSSA->dominates(NewDef, FirstDef).  │
│ This occurs during LICM's loop promotion when we insert synthesized stores    │
│ into loop exit blocks and then update MemorySSA. The assertion indicates the  │
│ newly inserted MemoryDef should dominate the first MemorySSA def in successor │
│ processing, but that condition is not met.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\nThe    │
│ log indicates the first transformation point is within                        │
│ MemorySSAUpdater::fixupDefs, called via MemorySSAUpdater::insertDef from      │
│ LoopPromoter::insertStoresInLoopExitBlocks. The reproducer exercises the path │
│ where LICM promotes a loop-carried memory location and inserts stores in exit │
│ blocks. The debug-only output confirms LICM is running with MemorySSA, and    │
│ the backtrace shows the crash right after creating and inserting a new        │
│ MemoryDef for the store in the exit block. No other earlier transformations   │
│ are reported.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\nIn                                  │
│ LoopPromoter::insertStoresInLoopExitBlocks, when we don't have a specific     │
│ MemorySSA insertion point (MSSAInsertPoint == nullptr), we create the         │
│ MemoryAccess at the \"Beginning\" of the exit block:\n  NewMemAcc =           │
│ MSSAU.createMemoryAccessInBB(NewSI, nullptr, NewSI->getParent(),              │
│ MemorySSA::Beginning);\nThis places the new MemoryDef at the start of the     │
│ block's MemorySSA access list, ahead of other accesses. However, LICM         │
│ synthesized store instructions are inserted at a concrete IR insertion point  │
│ (LoopInsertPts[i]) which may not correspond to the earliest MemorySSA access  │
│ in the block. As a result, MemorySSA order and IR order can become            │
│ inconsistent: a MemoryDef at the beginning of the block may not properly      │
│ dominate subsequent MemorySSA defs in successor processing because fixupDefs  │
│ assumes the MemorySSA placement reflects IR dominance and tries to wire       │
│ successors accordingly. This mismatch can lead fixupDefs to encounter a       │
│ successor's first def that it expects to be dominated by NewDef, but due to   │
│ the incorrect placement, the dominance relation breaks, triggering the        │
│ assertion.\n\nCritically, when there is already a local def in the block      │
│ occurring after our inserted store in IR, placing the MemorySSA def at the    │
│ beginning can cause fixupDefs to traverse successors instead of taking the    │
│ local-after path. Ensuring the newly created MemoryDef is placed at the end   │
│ of the block's MemorySSA access list aligns MemorySSA program order with the  │
│ actual IR insertion point for these synthesized stores and avoids violating   │
│ dominance in fixupDefs.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s):\n- File:                │
│ llvm/lib/Transforms/Scalar/LICM.cpp\n  Lines: 1848-1850\n  Change the         │
│ MemorySSA insertion location for newly created MemoryAccesses in loop exit    │
│ blocks from Beginning to End when no specific insert point is                 │
│ known.\n\nOld:\n  NewMemAcc = MSSAU.createMemoryAccessInBB(\n      NewSI,     │
│ nullptr, NewSI->getParent(), MemorySSA::Beginning);\n\nNew:\n  NewMemAcc =    │
│ MSSAU.createMemoryAccessInBB(\n      NewSI, nullptr, NewSI->getParent(),      │
│ MemorySSA::End);\n\nReasoning:\nPlacing the new MemoryDef at the end of the   │
│ block's MemorySSA access list matches the typical behavior of MemorySSA (new  │
│ accesses corresponding to IR inserted instructions are appended near their    │
│ program point) and ensures that if there is a local def after the operand,    │
│ fixupDefs will see it and only rename that local def, avoiding successor      │
│ traversal. This keeps the MemorySSA dominance consistent with IR, preventing  │
│ the assert in fixupDefs.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nThe crash is caused by            │
│ misplacement of MemorySSA defs for synthesized stores in exit blocks,         │
│ creating them at the beginning of the block's access list irrespective of the │
│ actual IR insertion position. Changing the default placement from Beginning   │
│ to End when MSSAInsertPoint is not provided aligns MemorySSA with IR, ensures │
│ proper dominance relations during fixupDefs, and prevents the assertion       │
│ failure. This fix is localized to LICM's                                      │
│ LoopPromoter::insertStoresInLoopExitBlocks and should resolve the reproducer  │
│ without impacting other LICM functionality."})                                │
