│                                                                               │
│ ### Root Cause Analysis ###                                                   │
│                                                                               │
│ -------------------- BEGIN --------------------                               │
│ 1. Understanding the Issue:                                                   │
│ The provided IR crashes opt with an assertion in MemorySSAUpdater::fixupDefs: │
│ MSSA->dominates(NewDef, FirstDef). This occurs during LICM's loop promotion   │
│ when we insert synthesized stores into loop exit blocks and then update       │
│ MemorySSA. The assertion indicates the newly inserted MemoryDef should        │
│ dominate the first MemorySSA def in successor processing, but that condition  │
│ is not met.                                                                   │
│                                                                               │
│ 2. Analyzing opt's Log:                                                       │
│ The log indicates the first transformation point is within                    │
│ MemorySSAUpdater::fixupDefs, called via MemorySSAUpdater::insertDef from      │
│ LoopPromoter::insertStoresInLoopExitBlocks. The reproducer exercises the path │
│ where LICM promotes a loop-carried memory location and inserts stores in exit │
│ blocks. The debug-only output confirms LICM is running with MemorySSA, and    │
│ the backtrace shows the crash right after creating and inserting a new        │
│ MemoryDef for the store in the exit block. No other earlier transformations   │
│ are reported.                                                                 │
│                                                                               │
│ 3. Root Cause Analysis:                                                       │
│ In LoopPromoter::insertStoresInLoopExitBlocks, when we don't have a specific  │
│ MemorySSA insertion point (MSSAInsertPoint == nullptr), we create the         │
│ MemoryAccess at the "Beginning" of the exit block:                            │
│   NewMemAcc = MSSAU.createMemoryAccessInBB(NewSI, nullptr,                    │
│ NewSI->getParent(), MemorySSA::Beginning);                                    │
│ This places the new MemoryDef at the start of the block's MemorySSA access    │
│ list, ahead of other accesses. However, LICM synthesized store instructions   │
│ are inserted at a concrete IR insertion point (LoopInsertPts[i]) which may    │
│ not correspond to the earliest MemorySSA access in the block. As a result,    │
│ MemorySSA order and IR order can become inconsistent: a MemoryDef at the      │
│ beginning of the block may not properly dominate subsequent MemorySSA defs in │
│ successor processing because fixupDefs assumes the MemorySSA placement        │
│ reflects IR dominance and tries to wire successors accordingly. This mismatch │
│ can lead fixupDefs to encounter a successor's first def that it expects to be │
│ dominated by NewDef, but due to the incorrect placement, the dominance        │
│ relation breaks, triggering the assertion.                                    │
│                                                                               │
│ Critically, when there is already a local def in the block occurring after    │
│ our inserted store in IR, placing the MemorySSA def at the beginning can      │
│ cause fixupDefs to traverse successors instead of taking the local-after      │
│ path. Ensuring the newly created MemoryDef is placed at the end of the        │
│ block's MemorySSA access list aligns MemorySSA program order with the actual  │
│ IR insertion point for these synthesized stores and avoids violating          │
│ dominance in fixupDefs.                                                       │
│                                                                               │
│ 4. Proposed Edit Point(s):                                                    │
│ - File: llvm/lib/Transforms/Scalar/LICM.cpp                                   │
│   Lines: 1848-1850                                                            │
│   Change the MemorySSA insertion location for newly created MemoryAccesses in │
│ loop exit blocks from Beginning to End when no specific insert point is       │
│ known.                                                                        │
│                                                                               │
│ Old:                                                                          │
│   NewMemAcc = MSSAU.createMemoryAccessInBB(                                   │
│       NewSI, nullptr, NewSI->getParent(), MemorySSA::Beginning);              │
│                                                                               │
│ New:                                                                          │
│   NewMemAcc = MSSAU.createMemoryAccessInBB(                                   │
│       NewSI, nullptr, NewSI->getParent(), MemorySSA::End);                    │
│                                                                               │
│ Reasoning:                                                                    │
│ Placing the new MemoryDef at the end of the block's MemorySSA access list     │
│ matches the typical behavior of MemorySSA (new accesses corresponding to IR   │
│ inserted instructions are appended near their program point) and ensures that │
│ if there is a local def after the operand, fixupDefs will see it and only     │
│ rename that local def, avoiding successor traversal. This keeps the MemorySSA │
│ dominance consistent with IR, preventing the assert in fixupDefs.             │
│                                                                               │
│ 5. Conclusion:                                                                │
│ The crash is caused by misplacement of MemorySSA defs for synthesized stores  │
│ in exit blocks, creating them at the beginning of the block's access list     │
│ irrespective of the actual IR insertion position. Changing the default        │
│ placement from Beginning to End when MSSAInsertPoint is not provided aligns   │
│ MemorySSA with IR, ensures proper dominance relations during fixupDefs, and   │
│ prevents the assertion failure. This fix is localized to LICM's               │
│ LoopPromoter::insertStoresInLoopExitBlocks and should resolve the reproducer  │
│ without impacting other LICM functionality.                                   │
│ --------------------  END  --------------------                               │
